The paper discusses a new approach to content-centric networking that provides native support for multicasting without the need for per-Interest forwarding state. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of simulation experiments to evaluate the proposed approach, which suggests that it may also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR), Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Information Theory (cs.IT), and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
